Implemented Vercel Web Analytics for Next.js App Router project

## Changes Made:

### 1. Installed Package
- Added `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1 to dependencies using pnpm
- Package manager: pnpm (as indicated by pnpm-lock.yaml)

### 2. Updated Files

**app/layout.tsx:**
- Imported `Analytics` component from '@vercel/analytics/next'
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag in the root layout
- Followed the official Next.js App Router integration pattern from Vercel documentation

**package.json:**
- Added "@vercel/analytics": "^2.0.1" to dependencies

**pnpm-lock.yaml:**
- Updated lock file with new dependency and its transitive dependencies

## Implementation Details:

According to the latest Vercel documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart), for Next.js App Router projects:
1. Import Analytics from '@vercel/analytics/next'
2. Place the `<Analytics />` component within the HTML body in the root layout

This implementation:
- Uses the framework-specific Next.js package ('@vercel/analytics/next')
- Places the Analytics component at the end of the body tag for optimal loading
- Preserves all existing code structure and formatting
- Maintains TypeScript compatibility

## Verification:

✓ Build completed successfully with no errors
✓ All type checking passed
✓ Lock file properly updated with pnpm
✓ No linting errors introduced

## Next Steps:

After deployment to Vercel:
1. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard's Analytics section
2. Verify analytics are working by checking browser Network tab for requests to `/_vercel/insights/*`
3. Analytics data will begin appearing in the Vercel dashboard

The analytics component is now ready and will automatically start tracking page views once the project is deployed to Vercel and Web Analytics is enabled in the dashboard.
